<br>
The Fire represents the unquenchable, burning desire of our members to become the ultimate embodiment of their respective classes. The Fire is that smouldering ember of excitement our members feel when we log on each day to conquer new obstacles or approach old ones with the goal of refining our methods to the point of perfection.<br>
<br>
The Fury represents the focusing and unleashing of our members’ passion and skill to achieve our individual and collective goals. The Fury is the unrelenting quest of our guild to decimate our opponents with skill and artistry.<br>
<br>
The Fire and The Fury is the synergy created by channelling our combined enthusiasm, enjoyment and talent towards the goal of becoming the best of the best.<br>
<br>
The Arch and the Four Pillars:<br>
<br>
Fire and Fury is guided and governed by an ideolgy that is embodied in the following symbols and concepts. <br>
<br>
The Arch:<br>
<br>
The Arch is a symbol of skilful artisanship, aesthetic beauty, and overwhelming strength. When properly positioned against an obstacle or opponent, the power of the Arch cannot be defeated. The Arch represents the distillation of our members’ abilities, focused by the will of our leadership. The Arch is the collective and expressed power of our entire guild.<br>
<br>
The Four Pillars:<br>
<br>
The concept of the Arch rest upon the axioms of the Four Pillars. Without the support of the Four Pillars, the power of the Arch cannot be properly focused nor maintained.<br>
<br>
The First Pillar – Dedication:<br>
<br>
All members of Fire and Fury must be dedicated to assisting individual members and the guild as a whole. This dedication is realized by focusing on what is better for the collective rather than just the individual. The fruits of dedication can be found in physical improvement (the acquisition of items of power) and spiritual growth (helping one another and fostering enjoyable relationships).<br>
<br>
The Second Pillar – Proficiency:<br>
<br>
All members of Fire and Fury are not expected to be merely competent – they are expected to be among the finest examples of their class. The grit and mortar of this pillar is constructed by the continual quest of our members to experience, learn, reflect, implement and adapt. Every member represents a segment of the pillar with each segment being key to the stability of the whole. <br>
<br>
The Third Pillar – Respect:<br>
<br>
All members of Fire and Fury will afford respect to one another. It is not expected that every member of our guild get along with every other member, all of the time. However it is expected that our members appreciate the concept of basic, human civility and will exercise it when situations demand it. This principal also extends to dealings with persons not in our guild.<br>
<br>
The leadership must respect the needs and desires of the membership and will endeavour to satisfy those demands. The membership must respect the machinations and goals of the leadership and will seek to assist the leadership in achieving the guild’s objectives.<br>
<br>
The Fourth Pillar – Enjoyment:<br>
<br>
It is the duty of the leadership to assist the membership in maximizing the enjoyment received from being a part of Fire and Fury. By the same token, the membership is expected to do what is necessary to help foster their personal enjoyment and the collective enjoyment of the guild. Without the Fourth Pillar, the weight of the Arch becomes oppressive and places great strain upon the other three pillars. Thus, the maintenance of the Fourth Pillar is a continual responsibility of the individual and the collective.<br>
<br>
The Leadership:<br>
<br>
Fire and Fury is not a democracy, nor is it a democratic republic. Fire and Fury is a benevolent dictatorship governed by a council whose objective is to maximize the abilities of the membership, focus those abilities to realize the collective goals of the guild, and foster an atmosphere of enjoyment for the members of Fire and Fury.<br>
<br>
The leadership is open to the constructive criticisms and suggestions of the membership. The proper channels for criticism and suggestion will be made readily evident and available to the membership. The membership must realize that no leadership is infallible and likewise that disagreeable short-term decisions are often the result of a more agreeable long-term goal.<br>
<br>
The leadership is in place for the benefit of the membership.<br>
